<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-12-19T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-12-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="683" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d683">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 123.R27/74.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 1126.</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-12-19">
                                    <hi rend="italic">December 19, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The body of the late Ambassador will be conducted from Dorchester House
                            with military escort on Saturday morning, December 21st, at ten o’clock.
                            The British cruiser <hi rend="italic">Natal</hi> will bear the body,
                            sailing from Portsmouth Saturday afternoon, to arrive at New York on the
                            morning of January third. Mrs. Reid asks me to say that nothing could
                            exceed in kindness the English care and the thoughtfulness of the
                            Government and all classes of the community.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Laughlin.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>